<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. Description of the Country around Lakes Superior and Huron, 1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0018</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">and every Shelf and Vein filled with shrubs and evergreens Sometimes meandering in festoons at others Spreading like a hanging Garden where the Rock admits their fastening by its Reclining backwards, makes altogether a piece of Scenery scarsely to be matched in Any part of the World<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The Second Recess now opens before You, not only <span class="DelHand-author">Reliev</span><span class="AddHand-author">Consol</span>ing the mind from the prospect of Safety it affords; but agreeably Relieving the eye by the soft contrast from Stern grandeur to Rural simplicity<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The beach is a fine White Sand the land gently rising behind; in the left corner Runs a beautiful limpid Rill and as you approach you are led to think you see the Ruins of Ancient Temples in which You are confirmed from perceiving an Arch standing quite apart from the neighboring Rocks, on the Summit of which (which is a Slate not 2 feet thick covered with 5 or 6 inches of mould) there is now growing Several Birch and Pines<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Not more than <span class="AddHand-author">one</span> quarter of a mile back from the Bay there is a Lake perhaps a mile <span class="AddHand-author">in</span> circumference Surrounded nearly by perpendicular Rocks &#8211; the little Rill takes its rise from it<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  It is very Remarkable that on all the mountains which Surround the Lake on either Side, there are Lakes, Some of</p>

